{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VtRKswksNrD989bBJMRwLE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Key test at line 115-120:\n```javascript\nit(\"preserves all-caps titles\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"chocolate cake\"], [\"ingredients\"]);\n  const text = \"CHOCOLATE CAKE\\nIngredients\\n200g flour\";\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"CHOCOLATE CAKE\");\n});\n```\n\nAnd at line 196-203:\n```javascript\nit(\"keeps 2-word ALL_CAPS join over its single-word prefix (ARAYES-type)\", async () => {\n\n\n```\n\nI'm looking at a series of test cases that verify the function preserves all-caps titles in various formats—from simple two-word titles like \"ARAYES SHRAK\" to longer Polish dish names like \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\", and compound titles with plus signs like \"MILK FLATBREADS + POTATO FLATBREADS\". The tests confirm the function handles single-word all-caps entries like \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" consistently across different scenarios, and continues through multi-word all-caps titles like \"BARSZCZ CZERWONY\".\n\nThis creates a conflict with Pattern E from the plan, which proposes converting all-caps text to title case. That transformation would break these existing tests—turning \"CHOCOLATE CAKE\" into \"Chocolate Cake\" when the test explicitly expects the all-caps version to remain unchanged. The plan describes this as optional and focused on improving user-facing quality, but the test suite clearly validates that all-caps titles should be preserved as-is, not normalized to title case.\n\n```\n\nSince the requirement is that all existing tests must pass, I can't implement Pattern E without also updating the tests themselves. I'll skip it and focus on patterns that don't conflict with the current test expectations.\n\nNow I'm checking whether Pattern G (adding a penalty for longer subtitles at positions 1-2) 